TY  - JOUR
AB  - Wage payments differ greatly in kind, being related not only to the period of time covered, but also to the value of the money in which they are paid. The economic welfare of the working class is dependent primarily upon the size of its average real annual earnings. Real annual earnings in turn depend upon hourly or piece wage rates, the number of hours worked or pieces turned out per annum, and the prices of the goods commonly bought by the wage earners. In many cases, hourly wage rates are but loosely correlated with the real earnings of labor. Frequently, indeed, high wage rates produce unemployment, and hence result in low annual earnings. This is true because higher wage rates tend to make higher wage costs, higher priced goods, and hence fewer sales. In many cases, wage rates for a given group are high not primarily because the services of this particular class of labor are especially desired by the public, but merely because the supply of the labor in question is controlled by a monopoly.
AU  - King, Willford I.
